1. Compute Options in Google Cloud
GCP's compute services are categorized as IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service) and Serverless (which fall under PaaS). We are starting with the IaaS pillar.

Compute Service Map:

GOOGLE CLOUD COMPUTE OPTIONS
├── IAAS (Server-Based)
│   ├── 1. Compute Engine (Virtual Machines)  ← WE ARE HERE
│   ├── 2. Kubernetes Engine (GKE)            ← Container Orchestration
│   └── 3. App Engine                         ← Early PaaS, but managed server
│
└── SERVERLESS (PaaS - No server management)
    ├── 4. Cloud Run
    ├── 5. Cloud Functions
    └── 6. App Engine (Flex/Standard)

Compute Engine = Virtual Machine: In GCP terminology, Google calls its VMs "Compute Engine" instances. Other clouds use different names (AWS: EC2, Azure: Virtual Machines).
Why GCP is Different: Google uses the same infrastructure for GCP that it uses for Gmail, Search, and YouTube. You get the same hardware quality and reliability.

2. Unique GCP Features (Competitive Advantage)
Custom Machine Types: Unlike other clouds where you pick from a fixed menu, GCP allows you to choose the exact amount of vCPU and RAM you need (using a slider), saving you money if you don't fit a standard size.
Encryption by Default: GCP encrypts all data at rest by default. In other clouds, this is often optional or requires manual enabling.
Hypervisor: GCP uses the KVM (Kernel-based Virtual Machine) hypervisor on its backend.
Comparison: AWS uses Nitro Hypervisor, Azure uses Hyper-V.
Fast Boot Time: GCP claims the fastest boot time among top cloud providers (approx. 30 seconds).
Per-Second Billing: GCP was the first cloud to introduce per-second billing (with a 1-minute minimum).
Example: If you run a VM for 1 min 10 sec, you pay for 1 min 10 sec. If you run it for 30 sec, you pay for 1 min.

