Family Breakdown (Series):

General Purpose (E2, N2, N2D):

E2: Entry-level, lowest cost. For small tasks, microservices.
N2: Balanced price/performance. For web serving, backend office.
N2D: Scale-out optimized, larger workloads.

Compute Optimized (C2, C2D):

Maximum vCPUs. For heavy computational work (scientific modeling, high-performance computing, gaming servers).
Note: "D" suffix means AMD processor is used.

Memory Optimized (M1, M2):

Maximum RAM (up to 3.75TB+).
For in-memory databases (SAP HANA), large data processing.

Accelerator Optimized (A2):

Attached GPUs. For Machine Learning, AI training, and video transcoding.

B. Shared-Core Machines

Not a "family" but a special type. You share a physical CPU core with other users temporarily.
Used for small, short-duration workloads. Very cost-effective.

Example: f1-micro, e2-micro.

C. Sole-Tenant Nodes

A dedicated physical server for your exclusive use.

Why use it?

Bring Your Own License (BYOL): If you have existing Windows or software licenses, you can apply them here to avoid double-paying for licenses in GCP.
Security/Isolation: To ensure no other customer's VM runs on your hardware.

D. Custom Machine Types

You define exact vCPU and RAM.

Crucial Rules for Custom VMs:

vCPU: Must be even numbers (2, 4, 6, 8... not 5, 7, 9). (Exception: 1 vCPU is allowed).
RAM: Must be in multiples of 0.25 GB (e.g., 4.5, 4.75, 5.00, 5.25 GB are allowed; 4.7 GB is not).
Ratio: RAM scales with vCPUs. Higher vCPU limits allow higher RAM ceilings.

5. Local SSD (Temporary Storage)
Definition: Directly attached, physically local storage to the physical host. # we cant run OS in local SSD
Persistence: Data is ephemeral (deleted if the VM is stopped or terminated).

Usage: Ideal for temporary scratch space, cache, or high-speed processing where data loss is acceptable.
Sizes: 375GB min to 3TB max per disk. Cannot be used to boot the OS.

